The paper discusses the use of recurrent neural networks (RNNs) for analyzing functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) data, which is a common application of machine learning and artificial intelligence in the field of neuroscience. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are likely sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of independent component analysis (ICA) and spatial maps, which are common in computer vision and image processing, suggesting cs.CV (Computer Vision) as another likely sub-category. The use of RNNs also suggests cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the analysis of temporal and spatial dynamics, which could be relevant to natural language processing and speech recognition, suggesting cs.CL (Computation and Language) as a less likely but still possible sub-category.
